name: (~2~H_6_)Propan-2-one
Reason: The target compound is fully deuterated propan-2-one (acetone with all hydrogen atoms replaced by deuterium). The deuterium isotope has a higher atomic mass compared to hydrogen, which generally results in stronger van der Waals forces and higher boiling/melting points. For hydrocarbons, the isotopic substitution of hydrogen for deuterium typically adds roughly 3-4 degrees per deutero atom to the melting point. The basic unit, acetone, has a melting point of -94.9. Here we have six deuterium substitutions. Deuterium effect: 6 * (3 to 4) = 18 to 24. However, since isotopic substitution can have a less than additive effect, and deuterium substitution in ketones might have a subtler influence compared to hydrocarbons, the shift might be on the lower end. Accounting for this, an estimated adjustment of about 2-3 per deutero atom seems more reasonable.
